<div id="review_2708315801" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2708315801" />
    <a title="Phrodrick" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/67951314-phrodrick"><img alt="Phrodrick" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1545868348p2/67951314.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2708315801?book_show_action=true">Jun 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Phrodrick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Phrodrick" href="/user/show/67951314-phrodrick">Phrodrick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer2708315801&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2708315801" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14643307007657268281">Having previously read and greatly enjoyed Nobel Prize winner Naguib Mahfouz’s Cairo Trilogy I was looking forward to reading Arabian Nights and Days. By the end I was only happy that it was over. I have read the many four and five stars reviews and have no idea what those folks read. In deference to those who may ‘get; Arabian N and D as clearly, I did not, I considered this as a 3-star book. I can not bring myself to up star. <br/><br/>The set up is brilliant. The book opens on day 1002 with Pasha Shahr</span>
  <span id="freeText14643307007657268281" style="display:none">Having previously read and greatly enjoyed Nobel Prize winner Naguib Mahfouz’s Cairo Trilogy I was looking forward to reading Arabian Nights and Days. By the end I was only happy that it was over. I have read the many four and five stars reviews and have no idea what those folks read. In deference to those who may ‘get; Arabian N and D as clearly, I did not, I considered this as a 3-star book. I can not bring myself to up star. <br /><br />The set up is brilliant. The book opens on day 1002 with Pasha Shahriyar ending his serial murder of wives in favor of his love of story teller wife Shahrzad. She is now stuck with a man she cannot love because of the innocent blood on his hands. The city celebrates the end of the killing, but with no thought of the complicity of high governing officials and the rest of the enablers in what was years of cruel murder. <br /><br />This could have been and should have been short Twilight Zone like episodes of guilty people, faced with their complicity and condemned to the various circles of hell. Better yet, the crimes were committed against women, women should have had the lead in serving out justice. Instead we get a series of weak Faustian bargains that seduce the guilty and the innocent and result in frequently arbitrary slaughter, Worse, I think Mahfouz makes a passing effort to discount Shahrzad as the authoress of the original stories and the male point of view predominates to a degree as to exclude women as the agents of justice. <br /><br />In other words, no delivery on the set up. <br /><br />The style of the storytelling is in keeping with the style of the original 1001 days. This is a reasonable choice, but makes it less accessible to a western reader. This is too bad for the western reader. The result is very little depth in the study of most of the characters. Almost all begin as they were, agree to become what they bargain for and then are not who they were. The result is anything but Raskolnikov.<br /><br />This could have been great literature. It could have been a wonderful use of classic Arabian story telling. Arabian Nights and Days is not.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14643307007657268281" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

