<div id="review_975926660" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/975926660" />
    <a title="Evey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12157494-evey"><img alt="Evey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1594342919p2/12157494.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/975926660?book_show_action=true">Jun 23, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Evey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Evey" href="/user/show/12157494-evey">Evey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer975926660" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9394094561536555698">Beneath the surface, in the depths of consciousness, lie the shadows that poison and ruin, their maws salivating at the prospect of devouring from within and without. In Arabian Nights and Days, the shadows manifest through the jinn, their draw and provocation the catalyst that breed the inhuman condition. This is portrayed in Qumqam, Zarmabaha, and the owner of the Invisibility Cap, mystical beings that corrupt and influence the imperfect souls of Sanaan al-Gamali, the reputable men of the city</span>
  <span id="freeText9394094561536555698" style="display:none">Beneath the surface, in the depths of consciousness, lie the shadows that poison and ruin, their maws salivating at the prospect of devouring from within and without. In Arabian Nights and Days, the shadows manifest through the jinn, their draw and provocation the catalyst that breed the inhuman condition. This is portrayed in Qumqam, Zarmabaha, and the owner of the Invisibility Cap, mystical beings that corrupt and influence the imperfect souls of Sanaan al-Gamali, the reputable men of the city, and Fadil Sanaan. These manifestations pull out the basest emotions of the heart and soul, despair, lust, and the promise of power the gateway to chaos and atrocities. Once enslaved to the shadows, their salvation come at a heavy price. Perhaps, it is in the realization that the soul has these shadows within that civilizations can rise above inhumanity. If only God is perfection, surely humans can aspire. That is what separates humankind form animals and monsters. In embracing human fallibility, the oceans within will be pacified and its shadows brought into light.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9394094561536555698" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


